## upstream

OpenClaw v2026.4.15 release — streaming watchdog feature (referenced in release notes under "TUI/streaming" fix)

## what it does

Adds a client-side streaming watchdog to streaming HTTP response handlers. If no streaming delta is received for 30 seconds (configurable `streamingWatchdogMs`, 0 to disable), the handler automatically finalizes the response and resets to idle state.

This prevents "stuck streaming" where a response handler hangs indefinitely due to network issues, upstream drops, or abandoned streams — leaving the client waiting forever.

Key implementation points:
- `dispose()` method clears the pending timer on shutdown
- Configurable via `streamingWatchdogMs` context option
- Reset event is logged so users know to send a new message to resync
- Works for any streaming response, not just TUI

## why it fits nessie

Nessie's TypeScript backend makes streaming LLM calls. Any streaming response handler that gets abandoned (client disconnect, network timeout, upstream error) will leak state and potentially block subsequent requests. A FinalizationRegistry alone is insufficient — this watchdog actively detects and recovers from stuck streams.

## suggested implementation

```typescript
// src/infra/streaming-watchdog.ts

interface StreamingWatchdogOptions {
  timeoutMs?: number;  // default 30_000
  onTimeout?: () => void;
  onReset?: () => void;
}

class StreamingWatchdog {
  constructor(opts: StreamingWatchdogOptions = {}) {
    this.timeoutMs = opts.timeoutMs ?? 30_000;
    this.onTimeout = opts.onTimeout;
    this.onReset = opts.onReset;
  }

  start(): void {
    this._timer = setTimeout(() => {
      this.onTimeout?.();
    }, this.timeoutMs);
  }

  reset(): void {
    clearTimeout(this._timer);
    this.start();
    this.onReset?.();
  }

  dispose(): void {
    clearTimeout(this._timer);
    this._timer = undefined;
  }

  private _timer?: ReturnType<typeof setTimeout>;
  private timeoutMs: number;
  private onTimeout?: () => void;

## upstream

OpenClaw PR #67460 (+319/-1, 8 files)

## what it does

Adds `suppressIfOtherAgentMentioned?: boolean` to `InboundMentionPolicy`. When `true`, an always-on agent (`requireMention=false`) skips responding if another agent was explicitly mentioned in the same message.

## why it fits nessie

Nessie's Orchestrator agent is configured as always-on (`requireMention=false`) while Worker agents are on-mention only. When a user explicitly @mentions a Worker in a channel message, the Orchestrator currently also responds, creating duplicate/competing replies — a well-known noise problem in multi-agent setups.

This pattern directly solves the Orchestrator/Worker interference issue.

## suggested implementation

```typescript
// src/channels/mattermost/mention-policy.ts

interface InboundMentionPolicy {
  requireMention?: boolean;
  suppressIfOtherAgentMentioned?: boolean; // NEW
}

// In the mention resolution logic:
// 1. Detect all explicitly mentioned agent IDs in the message
// 2. If suppressIfOtherAgentMentioned=true AND other agents are mentioned:
//    - Skip the always-on agent response
//    - Allow only the explicitly targeted agent to respond
```

## Bug Summary

The embedded agent runtime crashes with `TypeError: assistantMsg.content.flatMap is not a function` when using the **MiniMax** provider (`MiniMax-M2.7-highspeed`). MiniMax returns `assistantMsg.content` as a **string**, but the runtime assumes it's always a `ContentBlock[]` and calls `.flatMap()` directly on it.

## Reproduction

1. Configure `minimax-portal/MiniMax-M2.7-highspeed` as the agent model
2. Send any message that triggers an embedded agent run
3. The run ends with error: `assistantMsg.content.flatMap is not a function`

## Log Evidence

```
{"subsystem":"agent/embedded","event":"embedded_run_agent_end","isError":true,
 "error":"assistantMsg.content.flatMap is not a function",
 "model":"MiniMax-M2.7-highspeed","provider":"minimax-portal",
 "rawErrorPreview":"assistantMsg.content.flatMap is not a function"}
```

Source: `subsystem-CJEvHE2o.js:453`

## Root Cause

The Anthropic/OpenAI SDKs return `content` as `ContentBlock[]` (array of `{type, text}` objects), but **not all providers follow this convention**. MiniMax returns `content` as a plain `string`. The embedded agent runtime doesn't normalize before calling array methods:

```javascript
// Current code (assumes array):
assistantMsg.content.flatMap(block => ...)
```

When `content` is a string, `.flatMap()` doesn't exist → TypeError.

This is a class of bugs. We've seen the same pattern before with `content.trim is not a function` in downstream plugins.

## Suggested Fix

Add a `normalizeAssistantContent()` utility that coerces any `content` shape into `ContentBlock[]`:

```typescript
function normalizeAssistantContent(content: unknown): ContentBlock[] {
  if (typeof content === 'string') {
    return content.length > 0 ? [{ type: 'text', text: content }] : [];
  }
  if (Array.isArray(content)) {
    return content;
  }
  if (content == null) {
    return [];
  }
  // Fallback: stringify unknown types
  return [{ type: 'text', text: String(content) }];
}
```

